'''Frederick Steven Roach''' (born March 5, 1960) is an American [[boxing]] trainer and former professional boxer. Roach is widely regarded as one of the best boxing trainers of all time.<ref>http://www.boxinginsider.com/columns/freddie-roach-best-business/</ref> He is the enduring boxing coach of the [[Octuple champion|eight-division world champion]] [[Manny Pacquiao]], five-time and four-division world champion [[Miguel Cotto]], former [[World Boxing Council|WBC]] Middleweight Champion [[Julio César Chávez Jr.]], defensive master and  three-time world champion [[James Toney]], former UFC Middleweight and eleven-time Welterweight Champion [[Georges St-Pierre]], as well as top prospects [[Jose Benavidez]],<ref>[http://www.toprank.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=23700&ATCLID=204912005 Profile of Roach-trained prospect Benavidez – Top Rank Boxing] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717075130/http://www.toprank.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=23700&ATCLID=204912005 |date=2011-07-17 }}</ref> [[Peter Quillin]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eastsideboxing.com/news.php?p=23659&more=1|title=265-001 - Boxing News 24/7|date=24 January 2014|publisher=}}</ref> and [[Vanes Martirosyan]]. Roach was the trainer of two-time women's world champion [[Lucia Rijker]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.boxingnewsandviews.com/2016/03/16/freddie-roach-career-11418/|title=A Quick Guide To The Freddie Roach Career|website=Boxing News and Views|access-date=2016-04-25}}</ref> He has also trained former junior welterweight champion [[Amir Khan (British boxer)|Amir Khan]].

==Boxing career==
Roach was trained by his father Paul Roach at a young age along with his brothers Joey and Pepper. As a teenager, he was a dominant force in the [[New England]] amateur and AAU ranks.  Roach turned pro in 1978, fighting as a [[lightweight]] and won his first 10 bouts. Roach trained under legendary trainer [[Eddie Futch]] and went 26–1 before appearing in a historic match at the [[Boston Garden]] on June 11, 1982.

The card that night was the first of two times that all three Fighting Roach Brothers appeared at the same time.

Brothers Joey and Pepper won their undercard bouts but in the main event, Freddie lost a unanimous decision to Rafael Lopez. Freddie would rebound and go on to contend twice for regional championships. 

Late in his career, Roach, who was known for being able to take on a barrage of punches, began showing early signs of [[Parkinson's disease]]. Futch asked Roach to retire but the boxer refused and continued to fight with his father as his trainer. He went on to lose five of his last six fights before retiring at age 26. His best payday was $7,500.

