==Boxing trainer==
After his retirement from fighting, Roach worked in a variety of jobs around Las Vegas including [[telemarketing]] and a [[busboy]] before taking a job with his former trainer and mentor [[Eddie Futch]] as an unpaid assistant in 1986.<ref>[http://www.thesweetscience.com/boxing-article/3482/freddie-roach-takes-center-stage/ Thesweetscience.com]  {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090918222418/http://www.thesweetscience.com/boxing-article/3482/freddie-roach-takes-center-stage/ |date=September 18, 2009 }}</ref> He excelled in his new position and worked as Futch's assistant for five years.

In 1991, actor [[Mickey Rourke]] returned to boxing midway through his acting career, and hired Roach to train him in [[Hollywood, California]]. In 1995, when Rourke decided to quit boxing, he gave gym equipment to Roach, and it can be found in the Wild Card Boxing Club on Vine Street.

Roach owns the Wild Card Boxing Club in Los Angeles and works alongside his brother Pepper.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.doghouseboxing.com/DHB/Tyler110309.htm|title=Pepper Roach Interview on Manny Pacquiao vs Miguel Cotto, Floyd Mayweather Jr, James Toney, Oscar De La Hoya, Bernard Hopkins, Prediction and More!|publisher=}}</ref> He is one of the most popular trainers in boxing.{{citation needed|date=June 2013}} Roach's prized ward is [[Octuple champion|eight-division world champion]] [[Manny Pacquiao]]. Roach also once trained [[Oscar De La Hoya]] for his [[De La Hoya-Mayweather|May 5, 2007 superfight]] against [[Floyd Mayweather Jr.]]. His first world champion was [[Virgil Hill]], whom he took over from his own former trainer, [[Eddie Futch]]. He is also the former trainer for British boxers [[Gary Stretch]] (former WBC super welterweight Champion) Training Stretch for his WBO Middleweight Championship challenge against [[Chris Eubanks]] and [[Amir Khan (British boxer)|Amir Khan]], who became the [[World Boxing Association|WBA]] Light Welterweight Champion on July 18, 2009 and the [[International Boxing Federation|IBF]] Light Welterweight Champion on July 23, 2011, under Roach's tutelage. Roach also trains welterweight boxer [[Zachary Wohlman|Zachary "Kid Yamaka" Wohlman]] among many others.<ref name="laweekly1">{{cite web|last=Chelin |first=Pamela |url=http://www.laweekly.com/publicspectacle/2012/08/16/zachary-wohlman-aka-kid-yamaka-is-boxings-great-jewish-hope |title=Zachary Wohlman, aka 'Kid Yamaka,' Is Boxing's Great Jewish Hope |publisher=LA Weekly |date=October 3, 2013 |accessdate=March 31, 2014}}</ref><ref name="fightnetwork1">{{cite web|url=http://fightnetwork.com/news/28609:zachary-wohlman-a-k-a-kid-yamaka/ |title=Zachary Wohlman, a.k.a. Kid Yamaka |publisher=Fight Network |date= |accessdate=March 31, 2014}}</ref> {{citation needed span|text=Roach has trained 27 world champions to date|date=August 2015}} and can usually be seen nearby when his boxers are interviewed.

In the world of [[mixed martial arts]] (MMA), Roach has trained former [[Ultimate Fighting Championship|UFC]] Heavyweight Champion [[Andrei Arlovski]] and was one of his primary trainers for Arlovski's victory over [[Ben Rothwell]] on July 19 at [[Affliction Entertainment|Affliction]]'s inaugural show.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/mma/news?slug=ys-mmaweekaa071108&prov=yhoo&type=lgns|title=Boxing's Freddie Roach working with Andrei Arlovski|publisher=}}</ref> He has also trained MMA fighter [[Dan Hardy]] for his fight with [[Marcus Davis]] at UFC 99 as well as MMA greats, [[Tito Ortiz]], [[Anderson Silva]], and [[BJ Penn]]. In May 2010, he began a training engagement with [[Georges St-Pierre]] in advance preparation for the fighter's successful [[Ultimate Fighting Championship|UFC]] [[Welterweight (MMA)|welterweight]] title defense against [[Josh Koscheck]] at [[UFC 124]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cagepotato.com/it-begins-gsp-honing-his-knuckle-game-freddie-roach|title=It Begins: GSP Honing His Knuckle-Game With Freddie Roach - Cagepotato|publisher=}}</ref> Roach has also trained many other prominent mixed martial artists, such as: pro-boxer and kickboxer, and former [[List of EliteXC Champions#Lightweight Championship|EliteXC Lightweight Champion]], [[K.J. Noons]],<ref>[http://mmajunkie.com/news/14332/former-elitexc-champ-k-j-noons-drops-decision-in-weekend-boxing-bout.mma Former EliteXC champ K.J. Noons drops decision in weekend boxing bout] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100208190953/http://mmajunkie.com/news/14332/former-elitexc-champ-k-j-noons-drops-decision-in-weekend-boxing-bout.mma |date=2010-02-08 }} NMAjunkie.com</ref> [[Roger Huerta]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rogerhuerta.com/bio.html|title=Roger Huerta|publisher=}}</ref> and [[Rameau Thierry Sokoudjou]].<ref>[http://www.watchkalibrun.com/2009/4/30/860473/freddie-roach-really-likes Freddie Roach really likes training NMA fighters] – Watch Kalib Run</ref> In March 2010, Roach expressed interest in wanting to train former [[List of Pride champions#World Heavyweight Championship|Pride FC]] and WAMMA Heavyweight champion, [[Fedor Emelianenko]].<ref>[http://content.usatoday.com/communities/mma/post/2010/03/freddie-roach-reflects-on-mma-fighters-boxing-abilities/1 Freddie Roach ruminates on NMA fighters' boxing abilities] at the USATODAY.com</ref>

==Parkinson's disease==
Roach suffers from [[Parkinson's disease]].<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2008/dec/05/boxing-khan-roach | title = Big interview: Amir Khan's trainer Freddie Roach | work = The Guardian | author = Lawrence Donegan	| date = December 5, 2008 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.mmaweekly.com/absolutenm/templates/dailynews.asp?articleid=7910&zoneid=3 FREDDIE ROACH PREDICTS ARLOVSKI TO KO FEDOR- MMA WEEKLY – Mixed Martial Arts & UFC News, Photos, Rankings & more]</ref> 
As chronicled in the [[HBO]] series ''[[Real Sports with Bryant Gumbel]]'', he is able to actively control the disease through medication, injections and his training of boxers.  Roach's doctors feel that his active in-ring training routines with his fighters and tremendous [[eye-hand coordination]] that he has to exhibit have made it possible to slow the progress of the disease.

==Honors==
* Inducted into the World Boxing Hall of Fame, "Expanded Category" (Managers & Trainers).
* 2006 California Boxing Hall of Fame Inductee (Non-Boxer)
* 2003, 2006, 2008, 2009, 2010, 2013 & 2014 Boxing Writers Association of America Trainer of the Year
* 2008 World Boxing Council (WBC) "Lifetime Achievement Award"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abs-cbnnews.com/sports/10/14/08/pacquiao-coach-freddie-roach-gets-wbc-award|title=Pacquiao coach Freddie Roach gets WBC award|first=ABS-CBN|last=News|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://philboxing.com/news/story-19496.html|title=FREDDIE ROACH RECEIVES WBC AWARD|publisher=}}</ref>
* 2012 [[International Boxing Hall of Fame]], [[Canastota, New York|Canastota]], [[New York (state)|New York]], [[United States]] Non-participant Inductee (Trainer of World Champions)
* 2013 [[Nevada Boxing Hall of Fame]] Inaugural Inductee ("Trainers" Category)

