'''Jean-François-Marie d'Arquier de Barbegal''' (1761–1794), also known as de Baumelles,<ref>{{cite book |last=Masson |first=Paul R. |date=1931 |title=Les Bouches-du-Rhône: encyclopédie départementale |trans-title=The Bouches-du-Rhône: Departmental encyclopedia |url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=QeRnAAAAMAAJ&q=%22Arquier+%28Jean-Fran%C3%A7ois-Marie%29%22&dq=%22Arquier+%28Jean-Fran%C3%A7ois-Marie%29%22&hl=fr&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjN7ubwrYfPAhVClSwKHTd7DVsQ6AEIUDAJ |language=fr |location= |publisher=	Archives départementales des Bouches-du-Rhône |page=35 |quote=Arquier (Jean-François-Marie)}}</ref> [[Parliament of Aix-en-Provence|parliamentarian]] from [[Aix-en-Provence|Aix]] in the 18th century, was involved in the {{Interlanguage link multi|Federalism (French Revolution)|fr|3=Fédéralisme (Révolution française)|lt=federalist movement}} of 1793 during the [[French Revolution]].

== Biography ==
Jean-François-Marie Arquier was born in [[La Ciotat]] on June 17, 1761{{#tag:ref|AD (13) La Ciotat, Birth act, 1761, 30/57| group=n|name="Birth"}}. He is the son of François, ''Sieur de Barbegal'', Lord of Baumelles, and Françoise Richard.<ref name="Clapiers-Collongues">{{cite book |last1=Clapiers-Collongues |first1=Balthasar (de) |last2=Boisgelin |first2=Charles-Joseph-Eugène (de) |editor-last=Niel |editor-first=B. |date=1833 |title=Chronologie des officiers des cours souveraines de Provence |trans-title= |url=https://archive.org/stream/chronologiedeso00colgoog#page/n181/mode/2up/search/Arquier |language=fr |location=Paris |publisher=[[d:Q26861786|Société d’études provençales]] |page=157 |quote=Arquier (Jean-François-Marie)}}</ref>  He became [[counsellor to the parliament|advisor]] to the [[Parliament of Provence|Parliament]] in Aix on June 28, 1782.<ref name="Clapiers-Collongues" />   Later he was initiated into a [[Masonic lodge]] in Aix, but remained there only two years, until 1786. {{#tag:ref|Lodge of Friendship, founded in 1772 by Messrs. D'Allard, [[d:Q15967320|D'Alphéran]] and D'Eymar.<ref name="Cubells" />  [[Bibliothèque nationale de France|BnF]], "Archives et manuscrits", Bossu (8), [http://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/btv1b10000007s/f142.item.zoom read online], "Arquier, seign. de Beaumelle, Jean-Marie d’"| group=n|name="Bossu"}}<ref name="Cubells">{{cite book |last=Cubells |first=Monique |date=1984 |title=La Provence des Lumières : les parlementaires d’Aix au 18e siècle |trans-title=Enlightenment Provence: parliamentarians from Aix in the 18th century |url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=beRnAAAAMAAJ |language=fr |location=Paris |publisher=Maloine }}</ref>  On the eve of the [[French Revolution]], he attended meetings of the nobility for the bailliage of Aix in 1789.<ref>{{cite book |last1=La Roque |first1=Louis (de) |last2=Barthelemy |first2=Edouard (de) |date=1861 |title=Catalogue des gentilshommes de Provence et de la principauté d’Orange qui ont pris part ou envoyé leur procuration aux assemblées de la noblesse pour l’élection des députés aux États généraux de 1789 |trans-title=Catalogue of the gentlemen of Provence and the Principality of Orange who was involved or sent their procurement at the meetings of the nobility for the election of deputies to the Estates-General of 1789 |url=http://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k5408128v/f9.item.r |language=fr |location=Paris |editor1-last=Aubry |editor1-first=Auguste |editor2-last=Dentu |editor2-first=E. |page=8 }}</ref>

Arquier embraced the {{Interlanguage link multi|Federalists (French Revolution)|fr|3=Fédéralistes|lt=federalist cause}} before the [[Reign of Terror]], then was sentenced to death by the Military Commission in [[Marseille]] on 26 Pluviose Year II (February 14, 1794).<ref>{{cite book |last1=Prudhomme |first1=Louis-Marie |author-link1=Louis-Marie Prudhomme |date=1797 |title=Histoire générale et impartiale des erreurs, des fautes et des crimes commis pendant la révolution française |trans-title=General History and impartial errors, mistakes and crimes committed during the French Revolution |url=https://books.google.fr/books?hl=fr&id=TcRfAAAAcAAJ&q=%22Arquier+%28Jean-Fran%C3%A7ois-Marie%29%22#v=snippet&q=%22Arquier%20%28Jean-Fran%C3%A7ois-Marie%29%22&f=false |language=fr |location=Paris |publisher=Rue des Marais, N° 20, Faubourg-Germain |page=19 |quote=Arquier (Jean-François-Marie)}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Beauchamp |first1=Alphonse (de) |author-link1=Alphonse de Beauchamp |last2=Coiffier de Verfeu |first2=Henri-Louis |date=1806 |title=Biographie moderne: ou dictionnaire de tous les hommes morts ou vivans qui ont marqué à la fin du 18e siècle et au commencement de celui-ci, et sur-tout dans le cours de la révolution française, par leurs vertus, leurs talens, leus malheurs ou leurs crimes, etc. |trans-title=Modern Biography: or Dictionary of all the men dead or alive that marked the end of the 18th century, and the beginning of this one, especially during the French Revolution, by their virtues, their talents, their misfortunes or their crimes, etc. |url=https://books.google.fr/books?hl=fr&id=SNY6AAAAcAAJ&q=%22Arquier+%28J.-Fr.-Mar%29%22#v=snippet&q=%22Arquier%20%28J.-Fr.-Mar%29%22&f=false |language=fr |location=Leipzig |editor1-last=Besson |editor1-first=P. J. |page=84 |quote=Arquier (J.-Fr.-Mar)}}</ref>

He was guillotined the following day, 27 Pluviose Year II (15 February 1794), in Marseille.<ref>{{cite book |last=Cabasse |first=Prosper |date=1826 |title=Essais historiques sur le Parlement de Provence: depuis son origine jusqu’à sa suppression |trans-title=Historical Essays on the Parliament of Provence: from its origin to its removal |url=https://archive.org/stream/essaishistorique01caba#page/n83/mode/2up |language=fr |volume=1 |location=Paris |publisher=A. Pihan Delaforest |page=32 |quote=Arquier (Jean-François-Marie d’)}}</ref>

